UPDATE songs SET lyrics = E'Jesse James was a lad who killed many a man\nHe robbed the Glendale train\nHe stole from the rich and he gave to the poor\nHe''d a hand and a heart and a brain\n\nPoor Jesse had a wife to mourn for his life\nThree children they were brave\nBut that dirty little coward that shot Mister Howard\nHas laid poor Jesse in his grave\n\nIt was Robert Ford that dirty little coward\nI wonder how he does feel\nFor he ate of Jesse''s bread and he slept in Jesse''s bed\nThen he laid poor Jesse in his grave\n\nPoor Jesse had a wife to mourn for his life\nThree children they were brave\nBut that dirty little coward that shot Mister Howard\nHas laid poor Jesse in his grave\n\nIt was on a Saturday night the moon was shining bright\nThey robbed the Glendale train\nWith the agent on his knees he delivered up the keys\nTo the outlaws Frank and Jesse James\n\nPoor Jesse had a wife to mourn for his life\nThree children they were brave\nBut that dirty little coward that shot Mister Howard\nHas laid poor Jesse in his grave\n\nIt was on a Wednesday night the moon was shining bright\nThey robbed the Union train\nAnd the people they did say for many miles away\nIt was robbed by Frank and Jesse James\n\nPoor Jesse had a wife to mourn for his life\nThree children they were brave\nBut that dirty little coward that shot Mister Howard\nHas laid poor Jesse in his grave' WHERE title = 'Jesse James';

UPDATE songs SET lyrics = E'The sun shines bright in the old Kentucky home\n''Tis summer the people are gay\nThe corn top''s ripe and the meadow''s in the bloom\nWhile the birds make music all the day\n\nWeep no more my lady\nOh weep no more today\nWe will sing one song for the old Kentucky home\nFor the old Kentucky home far away\n\nThey hunt no more for the possum and the coon\nOn the meadow the hill and the shore\nThey sing no more by the glimmer of the moon\nOn the bench by the old cabin door\n\nWeep no more my lady\nOh weep no more today\nWe will sing one song for the old Kentucky home\nFor the old Kentucky home far away\n\nThe head must bow and the back will have to bend\nWherever the people may go\nA few more days and the trouble all will end\nIn the field where the sugar canes grow\n\nWeep no more my lady\nOh weep no more today\nWe will sing one song for the old Kentucky home\nFor the old Kentucky home far away' WHERE title = 'My Old Kentucky Home';

UPDATE songs SET lyrics = E'The Camptown ladies sing this song\nDoo dah doo dah\nThe Camptown racetrack five miles long\nOh the doo dah day\n\nGoing to run all night\nGoing to run all day\nI''ll bet my money on a bob-tailed nag\nSomebody bet on the bay\n\nThe long-tailed filly and the big black horse\nDoo dah doo dah\nThey fly the track and they both cut across\nOh the doo dah day\n\nGoing to run all night\nGoing to run all day\nI''ll bet my money on a bob-tailed nag\nSomebody bet on the bay\n\nOld muley cow come on to the track\nDoo dah doo dah\nThe bob-tailed filly threw her over his back\nOh the doo dah day\n\nGoing to run all night\nGoing to run all day\nI''ll bet my money on a bob-tailed nag\nSomebody bet on the bay' WHERE title = 'Camptown Races';

UPDATE songs SET lyrics = E'I come from Alabama with my banjo on my knee\nI''m going to Louisiana my true love for to see\nIt rained all night the day I left the weather it was dry\nThe sun so hot I froze to death Susanna don''t you cry\n\nOh Susanna oh don''t you cry for me\nFor I come from Alabama with my banjo on my knee\n\nI had a dream the other night when everything was still\nI thought I saw Susanna a-coming down the hill\nThe buckwheat cake was in her mouth the tear was in her eye\nSays I I''m coming from the south Susanna don''t you cry\n\nOh Susanna oh don''t you cry for me\nFor I come from Alabama with my banjo on my knee\n\nI soon will be in New Orleans and then I''ll look around\nAnd when I find Susanna I''ll fall upon the ground\nBut if I do not find her then I will surely die\nAnd when I''m dead and buried Susanna don''t you cry\n\nOh Susanna oh don''t you cry for me\nFor I come from Alabama with my banjo on my knee' WHERE title = 'Oh Susanna';

UPDATE songs SET lyrics = E'I''ll tell you all a story about Omie Wise\nHow she was deluded by John Lewis''s lies\nHe told her to meet him at Adams''s spring\nHe''d bring her some money and other fine things\n\nShe met him at the spring where she did not fear\nSays now John Lewis let us go from here\nShe got up behind him and away they did go\nThey rode till they came where the deep river flowed\n\nNow Omie oh Omie I''ll tell you my mind\nMy mind is to drown you and leave you behind\nOh pity your infant and spare me my life\nLet me go rejected and not be your wife\n\nHe kissed her and hugged her and turned her around\nThen pushed her in deep water where he knew that she''d drown\nHe jumped on his pony and away he did ride\nAs the screams of poor Omie came down from the tide\n\nThe wretch was not punished until one day\nThey found Omie''s body and it floated away\nThey sent after John Lewis who tried for to flee\nThey caught him at old Hillsville in Adams County' WHERE title = 'Omie Wise';

UPDATE songs SET lyrics = E'Late last night when the boss man come home\nHe asked about his lady\nThe only answer he received\nShe''s gone with the Black Jack Davey\nShe''s gone with the Black Jack Davey\n\nGo saddle me up my milk white steed\nThe grey is not so speedy\nI''ll ride all night till the broad daylight\nTill I overtake my lady\nTill I overtake my lady\n\nHe rode and he rode till he came to the town\nAnd he searched till he found her\nShe was lying on a big four-poster bed\nIn the arms of the Black Jack Davey\nIn the arms of the Black Jack Davey\n\nWon''t you pull off them high heeled shoes\nAll made of Spanish leather\nWon''t you put on them low heeled shoes\nAnd we''ll ride home together\nAnd we''ll ride home together' WHERE title = 'Black Jack Davey';

UPDATE songs SET lyrics = E'As I was a-going on down the road\nWith a tired team and a heavy load\nI cracked my whip and the leader sprung\nI says day-day to the wagon tongue\n\nTurkey in the straw turkey in the hay\nRoll ''em up and twist ''em up a high tuckahaw\nAnd twist ''em up a tune called Turkey in the Straw\n\nWent out to milk and I didn''t know how\nI milked the goat instead of the cow\nA monkey sitting on a pile of straw\nA-winking at his mother-in-law\n\nTurkey in the straw turkey in the hay\nRoll ''em up and twist ''em up a high tuckahaw\nAnd twist ''em up a tune called Turkey in the Straw\n\nMet Mister Catfish coming down stream\nSays Mister Catfish what does you mean\nCaught Mister Catfish by the snout\nAnd turned Mister Catfish wrong side out\n\nTurkey in the straw turkey in the hay\nRoll ''em up and twist ''em up a high tuckahaw\nAnd twist ''em up a tune called Turkey in the Straw' WHERE title = 'Turkey in the Straw';
